\fs28 Integrated Find Files Command\fs20\par
\par
The standard windows Find Files utility is just beginning to catch up with the functionality offered by the 2xExplorer's internal item - and not in all departments. Still, you don't have to splash out for the latest version of Windows XP to have a decent file search utility, when 2xExplorer provides all these features for all earlier win32 platforms (9x/NT4 etc), too:\par
\pard{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf4\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li360 Multiple file filters (file types) to locate.\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}Many search "root" folders can be specified to look in.\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}Date-constrained searches can use all three pieces of file date stamp information (modified, created and accessed). The minimum timeslice supported is an \i hour\i0 , which may help pinpoint recently changed files.\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}Text-constrained searches can be refined by options like case sensitivity, word search, and the \i time-saving\i0  option to exclude binary files (regardless of exact type) from the searched list.\par
\pard\par
The find results window is a modeless dialog, which means that it can be left open without interfering with the normal operations in 2xExplorer. The main purpose served is to load and highlight the items found in one of the regular 2xExplorer panes, where any further operations may take place if need be. The range of supported commands in the results window itself is limited, as accessible via a context menu. In this sense it behaves differently to the standard windows Find Files utility; if you prefer the latter you can invoke it from within 2xExplorer using the shell context menu (right-clicking) on any folder item in the two panes or tree view.\par
\par
\f1 The search results can be printed using the context menu. Also you can create \b batch files\b0  using the standard command templates (see the batch file creation section below)\par
\f0\par
