\fs28 Advanced Features\fs20\par
\par
\f1 2xExplorer was developed for non-frustrating everyday use in mind. Following is a list of features that will be appreciated under this light, by all people poised with seeking maximum efficiency and optimization in their lives - some jealous and/or incompetent folk would maliciously use the term "control freaks" here.   :\'ac)\f0\par
\par
\ul\fs22 Efficient Folder Navigation\ulnone\fs20\par
There are so many different ways to move around your filesystem hierarchy that you are truly spoiled for choice:\par
\pard{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf4\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li360 Using the address bar to key in paths, or to select a folder browsed earlier from the drop-down history portion. Buttons/shortcuts for moving to parent/root/desktop folders will also be found here.\par
\f1{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}Dragging folders or files from your desktop and dropping them on the address bar is equivalent to typing their full path, and takes you directly to their location.\f0\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}Using the tree view to select any folder in all the filesystem hierarchy.\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}Using the DriveBar for quickly accessing all disc drives installed on your computer (a similar functionality is available via the Tools | Select Drive command).\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}Using the navigation chain, which allows moving to folders browsed earlier/after in the familiar Previous/Next mechanism popular with internet browsers. 2xExplorer also remembers the last item that had the focus and \i reinstates\i0  it when a folder is revisited.\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}Using the bookmarks, which are shared by both panes.\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}Many modeless dialogs that show filesystem trees (e.g. Folder Data, Find Files results) can also be used to change folder by double-clicking.\par
\pard\par
Since there is just one set of controls (e.g. tree, driveBar, miscellaneous buttons, etc.) shared among the two panes, any navigation command will normally affect the \i active\i0  pane. However, by holding down the \b\f2 <Alt>\b0\f0  key the command will be directed to the inactive pane. This is a very useful feature which importance for improving browsing efficiency cannot be overstated enough. The \f2 <Alt>\f0  modifier works universally for all browsing commands mentioned above, regardless if they are keyboard or mouse-oriented. For example, you can hold \f2 <Alt>\f0  while double-clicking on a folder displayed in the tree view, while pressing \f2 <Return>\f0  in the address bar, while using \f2 <Backspace>\f0  to move to the parent directory, and so on.\par
\par
\ul\fs22 Multi-purpose Address bar\ulnone\fs20\par
The address bar is multi-functional, accepting pathnames, visual filters or both at the same time. This is a handy feature allowing a single focal point to be used for all text-input requirements, doing away with the need for separate time-consuming sessions in dedicated dialog boxes that are found in rival file management applications.\par
\par
Concentrating on the addressing functionality, either absolute or relative paths are accepted, including any combinations of the parent (\f2 ".."\f0 ) and root (\f2 "\\"\f0 ) folder specifiers. In many occasions addressing a folder by its name is much faster than furiously clicking here and there, especially if the target folder is more than a single step away in the hierarchy tree. Finally, it should be noted that all the boxes that accept paths in 2xExplorer (throughout the application, as e.g. in the Copy dialog), have similar "smart" parsers supporting them, and are fully path-"conscious", both for relative and absolute paths. For instance the difference between \f2 "C:"\f0  and \f2 "C:\\"\f0  is properly resolved.\lang1033  \b UNC\b0  paths are also supported, allowing direct browsing of resources in other computers in a network (e.g. \f2 "\\\\\lang2057\f3 share\lang1033\f2\\~umeca74"\f0 ).\lang2057\f1  Paths may also include environmental variables like \i %WINDIR%\i0  which are automatically expanded according to your user profile settings. Finally, it is possible to include a filename as a part of the path, which results in browsing the folder and selecting the filename specified at the same time.\f0\par
\par
\lang1033 Except for addressing, the bar can also be used for entering commands to \b execute\b0 , for both DOS and 32-bit windows programs. In order to differentiate command execution from normal addressing, 2xExplorer interprets as commands inputs that begin with '\f2 $\f0 ' or '\f2 >\f0 ' characters. 2xExplorer also simplifies the compilation of argument lists, since it enables copying filenames from the active pane directly into the address bar, using \f2 <Ctrl+arrowKeys>\f0  to select names and \f2 <Ctrl+Return>\f0  to transfer them.\lang2057\f1  Path names are easily accessible with the $L and $R constructs, for the left and right pane respectively, as is the focused filename with $N (similar to the GenerateBatch command, see below). The tokens $P and $I stand for the active and inactive pane paths, respectively. Their use is similar to $L and $R but the former pair can be used for composing more generic reusable commands, independent on the pane that happens to be active. Finally environmental variables like \i %WINDIR%\i0  can be used as part of the commands — these are automatically expanded by 2xExplorer.\lang1033\f0\par
\lang2057\par
The drop-down portion of the folder address selection combo box lists the names of the folders that have been recently visited. This allows rapid switching backwards and forwards between folders, if need be. This list is different from the navigation chains maintained by each pane, since the latter are specific to each pane whereas the former is a shared resource.\par
\par
\lang1033\b Histories\b0  of other items entered in the address bar, like visual filters and commands, are also maintained. Naturally, there's no room for them in the drop-down portion; access is offered via items in the Files and Tools menus, respectively.\lang2057\par
\par
\ul\fs22 Smart Keyboard Shortcuts\ulnone\fs20\par
2xExplorer is also known as the "keyboard-junkie's"-Explorer. A design specification of the program is to provide keyboard shortcuts for all important and commonly used commands. Most accelerators are shown next to the respective menu command and are also included in the tooltips, acting as a quick reminder. For many useful "undocumented" shortcuts please refer to the accompanying \f2 Keyboard.txt\f0  file.\par
\par
2xExplorer caters for the needs of a sizeable portion of computer users who prefer the keyboard for applications they use daily. With long term use it is easy to memorise the keyboard equivalents of most frequently used commands, which enable one to do things with lightning speed compared to using the mouse - that's the typical "man or mouse" dilemma. Why bother with target practising or do battles with clogged up and foul mouse roller balls, when paradise is just an arm's length away? 2xExplorer won't test your patience when you use it daily, even after the initial impressions have been long since worn off. That's the recipe for healthy long-term "relationships" IMHO.\par
\par
Another useful attribute here is that the \f2 <Ctrl>\f0  key can be used to modify the behaviour of an accelerated command. For instance, the \f2 <F5>\f0  key used for copying will normally summon a dialog box, requesting the target folder for the operation. Although the "opposite" pane folder name will be usually pre-selected, and the only action required from the user would be a single Return key press for acceptance, wouldn't it be better if one could do away with the dialog box altogether? That is exactly what the Control key does as a modifier to commands like Copy: pressing \f2 <Ctrl+F5>\f0  will result in an \i immediate\i0  copy, dispensing with the dialog. All commands that use an intermediate dialog box and could somehow accept a default answer without any user intervention can be similarly modified using the Control key. For full details refer to \f2 Keyboard.txt\f0 .\par
\par
\ul\fs22 Folder Subtree Data\ulnone\fs20\par
Inquisitive minds will surely find the summary information offered by a standard property page of any folder to be rather on the brief and utterly unsatisfying side. 2xExplorer provides detailed information about a folder including detailed breakdown of the included files and sub-folders (and the respective storage space occupied) all the way down to the last sub-folder in the hierarchy tree.\par
\par
The results are presented in an intuitive tree fashion, hosted by a modeless (and resizable) dialog window, which can remain open for as long as one likes. That will help you to figure out exactly how on earth all these megaBytes managed to pile up in the windows directory.\par
\par
\f1 Right-clicking on this window opens a context menu which may be used to sort the items and even print the fully expanded tree of information.\f0\par
\par
\ul\fs22 Extended File Date Information\ulnone\fs20\par
All 3 pieces of file date/time information available (last Modified, first Created and last Accessed) are available in the details view - by selecting the relevant property from View | Options page - unlike the Explorer where only the last modified time can be seen. This feature, except for allowing easy access to file time stamp information, also enables the sorting of files using dates other than the modification one. This is useful in many cases where one would like to detect e.g. files that have been recently accessed (without being modified). Those nasty virus and/or install programs will no longer hide their activities from power users!\par
\par
\ul\fs22 Batch File Creation\ulnone\fs20\par
Except for the regular operations on selected files/folders, there is a special treat for all the old hands out there, that most probably would have wished for a similar capability all those years back in the dark DOS ages. Enter the batch file generator. Using a command template with special characters for the path/filename/extension, it is possible to apply the same series of commands on each selected item with minimum effort.\f1  The following special characters are supported in templates:\par
\b\f3 $N\b0\f1  for full filename (e.g. \f3 object.cpp\f1 )\par
\b\f3 $B\b0\f1  for base filename (e.g. \f3 object\f1 )\par
\b\f3 $E\b0\f1  for filename extension (e.g. \f3 cpp\f1 )\par
\b\f3 $L\b0\f1  for left pane full path name\par
\b\f3 $R\b0\f1  for right pane full path name\par
\b\f3 $P\b0\f1  for full path of the focused item's name\par
\b\f3 $I\b0\f1  for inactive pane's full path name\par
\b\f3 $xx\b0\f1  for an automatically incremented number (see explanation below)\par
\par
\f0 Typical uses of this command include the \b mass-renaming\b0  of file extensions (using a template as \f2 "ren $N $B.other"\f0 ), touching the date stamp information, and so forth. You'll surely regret deleting them ms/dos commands!\par
\par
The tokens $P and $I are generalizations of the $L and $R tokens and are preferred for building up a battery of reusable command templates. The active pane in 2xExplorer determines the \i current directory\i0  in the traditional DOS sense. The $L/$R tokens usually require a particular pane to be active for a command to be executed properly, whereas the new $P/$I break this assymetry. For instance whereas the command "copy $N $R" could only be used when the left (top) pane was active, its novel equivalent "copy $N $I" is valid from either left or right panes. The $P token is also extremely important for batch file generation from the find files result window, where items from many folders are displayed all at once. There $P correctly stands for the path of each item.\par
\par
\lang1033 Mass-renaming is made easier by using counters, which are numbers automatically incremented by one for each line generated. Name sequences like \f3 file01, file02,\'85\f0  are easy to construct with the special template \f2 "file$01"\f0 . You have the flexibility of specifying both the starting value of a counter and the number of leading zeros; for instance, the counter \f2 "$0012"\f0  will start counting from 12 and add enough leading zeros to ensure a 4-digit number.\lang2057\par
\par
\ul\fs22 Advanced file management\ulnone\fs20\par
Except for the normal copy/rename/delete file operations, 2xExplorer offers a range of advanced file management commands. \b Shredding\b0  completely destroys files by deleting them after first overwriting their contents with 0s. Large files may be \b split\b0  in chunks of specified sizes so as to e.g. fit on a floppy disk; these may be subsequently \b merged\b0  to recreate the original large file. File modification dates can be \b touched\b0  to synchronize them with the CPU clock.\par\par
Except for normal shortcuts, 2xExplorer can paste \b hard links\b0  to files and folders. Hard links are a more direct way for providing access to files from many locations since the direct file is exposed circumventing the requirement for a "pointer" shortcut file. Hard links look in all aspects like the original file, but point to the same physical disk location, hence storage is not wasted whilst changes made to a link automatically propagate to the original file (or vice versa). The major limitation is that both the original and the hard linked version must reside on the \i same\i0  NTFS partition.\par
\par
\ul\fs22 Command Line Arguments\ulnone\fs20\par
2xExplorer can be started with optional arguments (e.g. using a desktop shortcut). The command line can be used \cf1 to override various default program settings, and markedly so the initial directories displayed in its panes. The syntax is as follows:\par
\par
\f2 > 2xExplorer [leftFolder [rightFolder]] [/S:<name>]\f0\par
\par
All arguments are optional. The initial folder arguments can be utilised to make 2xExplorer the default file manager of your system; preferably you should specify full pathnames here. The \f2 /S\f0  option controls the registry key name where all the persistent program properties are kept (window size and the rest). By default, 2xExplorer will store everything in \f2 "HKEY_CURRENT_USER\\Software\\ZabaraKatranemia Plc\\2xExplorer"\f0 ; using the (for example) \f2 /S:OTHER\f0  argument will force properties to be stored/read from the \f2 "HKEY_CURRENT_USER\\Software\\ZabaraKatranemia Plc\\2xExplorerOTHER"\f0  key instead. This feature can be handy for keeping various shortcuts in your desktop, each with different settings.\par
\cf0\par
\ul\fs22 Layout Management\ulnone\fs20\par
2xExplorer uses advanced layout management to arrange the numerous toolbars that provide useful services. All bars can be either docked or floating, or even hidden if not required. Moving toolbars around is simple as long as you find an "empty" spot to drag them from. Holding \f2 <Ctrl>\f0  pressed will force a toolbar to float, so that it can be placed outside the main 2xExplorer frame window and/or resized. Special bars like the folder tree can be resized even while docked. The management algorithm permits having more than one bar sharing the same frame window edge while docked.\par
\par
Given the large number of possible toolbar arrangements, 2xExplorer offers a mechanism to "save" a number of favourite distinct layouts and re-apply them at will at a later stage. For instance you may have an image previewing "mode", where the thumb control has a prominent position and one regular pane is hidden, another for regular file management where the window is maximised, and so on. The layout manager allows rapid switching among such different functionality modes. The information retained includes: window size/position, toolbar visibility/dock state/size/position, left/right pane sizes, even the view style of the panes (details, large icons, etc.).\par
\par
\ul\fs22 General Usability\ulnone\fs20\par
The author has pledged for the utmost usability of this program. All dialog boxes offer reasonable suggestions so that you won't have to do much typing yourself. Even in case you do need a bit of typing, the most appropriate field will be usually pre-selected so one can start altering the information immediately and mouse-free. Another anti-typing measure is the maintenance of \b history\b0  items, so there is no need to re-type what you just entered a short while ago. As a matter of course, most boxes meant for keyboard editing will have a drop-down part carrying the recent history information (combo boxes).\par
\par
\f1 In order to make accessing previously typed information even easier, all combo boxes support \b autocompletion\b0 , which comes in handy when there are many strings in the history list. Just type in a few characters of the intended text, hit \f3 <up-arrow>\f1  and 2xExplorer will expand the string for you, searching the history list for the combo box in question. See Keyboard.txt for the full instructions.\f0\par
\par
All this history information is saved (in the registry) when you quit 2xExplorer, and is made available next time you restart the program. This holds true for all the program settings. Properties that affect the program operation (e.g. the overwrite confirmation in the Copy/Move dialog box), window sizes and positions, even the width of each column in the "Details" view, are \b persistent\b0  properties. So each time you restart 2xExplorer it's like you pick it up where you last left it - no messing about with resetting your favourite options.\par
\par
Finally, 2xExplorer makes good use of the status bar to communicate various important messages to the user, avoiding intrusive message boxes that require user intervention to get them out of the way. These status messages will clear themselves after 5 seconds or so without giving you any hassle. That's exactly the fundamental concept behind 2xExplorer: a set of simple yet important touches that make one's long term relationship with computers less of an irritant and more enjoyable.\par
\par
